        "name": "QoI relevance acceptance criteria — COU2",
        "description": "The primary QoI (normalized hemolysis index, NIH) must be directly linked to the clinical endpoint (plasma-free hemoglobin elevation) via a documented physiological pathway; secondary QoIs (wall shear stress distribution, scalar stress exposure time) must be shown to drive the primary QoI through the hemolysis power-law model."
      },
      "rationale": "NIH is the regulatory-recognized metric for hemolysis assessment per FDA guidance. Physiological linkage to plasma-free hemoglobin documented via Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model (τ, t exposure parameters). Sensitivity of NIH to wall shear stress and exposure time confirmed via one-at-a-time parameter sweeps. QoI hierarchy fully documented in the analysis plan. Gradation 4 achieved."
